docs.lead_paragraph: At the 2021 Grammys, Beyoncé picked up four awards, bringing her total to 28 and making her the winningest woman in Grammy history. At the 2023 ceremony, she will have nine chances to add to her total: The 41-year-old star is the top nominee for the 65th annual Grammy Awards, with all but one of her nods coming for her dance-heavy album “Renaissance.”

docs.abstract: In 1973, he put out a little-noticed album of songs about same-sex love and social protest. Forty-one years later, he became an unlikely star.
docs.snippet: In 1973, he put out a little-noticed album of songs about same-sex love and social protest. Forty-one years later, he became an unlikely star.
docs.lead_paragraph: Patrick Haggerty, who in 1973 released an album of country songs about same-sex romance that sold only 1,000 copies and seemed destined for eternal obscurity until, four decades later, its rediscovery brought him renown as the first openly gay country singer, died on Oct. 31 at his home in Bremerton, Wash. He was 78.

headline.main: Patrick Haggerty, ‘Lost Pioneer’ of Gay Country Music, Dies at 78

docs.lead_paragraph: Elizabeth Stewart, a folk singer, pianist and composer who furthered the legacy of her musical family and the culture of the ethnic grouping known as Scottish Travellers through her recordings, performances and musicology, died on Oct. 13 in the village of Kemnay, near Aberdeen, Scotland. She was 83.

docs.abstract: At 86, this eminent composer takes a surprising but still searching direction in his music, while recent projects look back on six decades of work.
docs.snippet: At 86, this eminent composer takes a surprising but still searching direction in his music, while recent projects look back on six decades of work.
docs.lead_paragraph: Steve Reich — one of our greatest living composers, with a recognizably pulsing sound and a place in the pantheon of Minimalist pioneers — recently turned 86. It’s not the clean kind of age, usually in multiples of five, that you often see observed with a concert like Carnegie Hall’s celebration in his name on Tuesday night. But that’s the pandemic-disjointed world we live in.

headline.main: Steve Reich, Busy as Ever, Enters His Late Period
